  "belgian-man": {
    "categories": ["featured", "community", "bmr"],
    "title": "Belgian Man Records",
    "year": "2007–2015",
    "github": "https://github.com/belgianman",
    "website": "http://www.belgianman.com",
    "tagline": "Experimental Record Label",
    "media": [{
      "type": "image",
      "url": "/images/belgianman.png"
    }],
    "slug": "belgian-man",
    "body": "<a href=\"http://belgianman.com/\">Belgian Man Records</a> is a record label I started in 2007.\n\nIn the beginning, I made a commitment to personally handle as many aspects as possible, and as a result I&#8127;m proud that my own hand has touched almost every release, be it through audio mastering, cover design, or full-on recording and production, and that I&#8127;ve personally done all the label&#8127;s promotion, web development, and management.\n\nRunning the operation, I&#8127;ve had the opportunity to design album covers, t-shirts, and posters, plan large events, record and produce albums, and work with dozens of creative people whom I&#8127;d never have met were it not for Belgian Man.\n\nYou can find my own releases and a collection of my cover designs on <a href=\"http://belgianman.com/monks\">my page at Belgian Man</a>.\n"
  },
  "chsh": {
    "categories": ["howto", "linux"],
    "title": "Use a non-standard shell on OSX",
    "year": "2015",
    "slug": "chsh",
    "body": "A \"non-standard shell\" is a shell that's not listed in /etc/shells. So, use `where <shell>` to find shell path, and add it to `/etc/shells`.\n\nThen `chsh -s <shell-path>`\n"
  },
  "tee": {
    "categories": ["howto", "linux"],
    "title": "save a read-only file in vim",
    "year": "2015",
    "slug": "tee",
    "body": "If you've opened a file read-only, or if you don't want to run `sudo vim` for some reason, you can use this trick to save the file anyway.\n\n    :w !sudo tee %\n\nBecause you're working around the official save behavior, it'll give you a warning that the file has changed on disk, and ask if you would like to reload it. It doesn't matter which option you pick: the version you saved is exactly the same as what's in your buffer already.\n"
  },
